---
/**
 * Hub: cost basis / lot matching. Worked example computed by costBasis().
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import CostBasisCalculator from '../../components/calculators/CostBasisCalculator.tsx';
import { costBasis } from '../../lib/capital-gains';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

// Two lots: 100 @ $10 held long-term, 100 @ $20 held short-term. Sell 100 @ $30.
const lots = [
  { shares: 100, cost: 1000, daysHeld: 400 },
  { shares: 100, cost: 2000, daysHeld: 100 },
];
const fifo = costBasis(lots, 'fifo', 100, 30);
const lifo = costBasis(lots, 'lifo', 100, 30);
const avg = costBasis(lots, 'average', 100, 30);
---

<Base
  title="Cost basis calculator — FIFO, LIFO, specific-lot gain"
  description="Work out the cost basis and the short vs long-term gain on a stock or fund sale, under FIFO, LIFO, specific-identification or average-cost lot matching."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">Capital gains</p>
    <h1>Cost basis calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">Which shares you sell decides your gain. Pick the method and see the difference.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    When you have bought the same stock at different prices and sell only some of
    it, the basis depends on which lots you are treated as selling. The default is
    FIFO — oldest first — but you can specifically identify lots, and funds often
    use average cost. The method changes your basis, your gain, and how much is
    long-term. Enter your lots and compare.
  </p>

  <CostBasisCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — two lots of 100 shares, selling 100 at {formatMoney(30)}</h2>
  <p>
    You bought 100 shares at {formatMoney(10)} over a year ago (long-term) and
    another 100 at {formatMoney(20)} recently (short-term). You sell 100 at
    {formatMoney(30)} — {formatMoney(3000)} of proceeds. The basis, and the gain,
    depend entirely on the method:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Basis</th><th>Gain</th><th>Short-term</th><th>Long-term</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>FIFO (oldest first)</td><td>{formatMoney(fifo.basis)}</td><td>{formatMoney(fifo.gain)}</td><td>{formatMoney(fifo.shortTermGain)}</td><td>{formatMoney(fifo.longTermGain)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>LIFO (newest first)</td><td>{formatMoney(lifo.basis)}</td><td>{formatMoney(lifo.gain)}</td><td>{formatMoney(lifo.shortTermGain)}</td><td>{formatMoney(lifo.longTermGain)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Average cost</td><td>{formatMoney(avg.basis)}</td><td>{formatMoney(avg.gain)}</td><td>{formatMoney(avg.shortTermGain)}</td><td>{formatMoney(avg.longTermGain)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    FIFO reports a {formatMoney(fifo.gain)} gain, all long-term — more gain, but at
    the lower rate. LIFO reports {formatMoney(lifo.gain)}, all short-term at
    ordinary rates. Same sale, {formatMoney(fifo.gain - lifo.gain)} apart in
    reported gain and taxed differently. Take the split into the
    <a href="/capital-gains-tax-calculator/">capital gains calculator</a> for the tax.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What is cost basis?</h3>
    <p>
      What you paid for an investment, including commissions and fees — the number
      subtracted from your sale proceeds to find the gain. For reinvested
      dividends and shares bought over time, basis is tracked lot by lot.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Which method should I use?</h3>
    <p>
      FIFO is the default and often maximizes long-term treatment. Specific
      identification gives the most control — you can sell your highest-basis lots
      to minimize the gain, or your loss lots to harvest losses — but you must
      designate the lots at the time of sale. Mutual funds commonly use average cost.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can I change methods later?</h3>
    <p>
      Once you use average cost for a fund, you generally must keep using it for
      shares already held. For individual stocks you can specifically identify
      lots at each sale. The rules differ by account and security, so confirm with
      your broker's records, which the IRS also receives on Form 1099-B.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How does the holding period work per lot?</h3>
    <p>
      Each lot has its own clock, running from the day after purchase. Selling
      across lots can produce both short and long-term gain on a single sale — the
      calculator splits them, because they are taxed at different rates.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/capital-gains-tax-calculator/">Capital gains tax calculator</a> — the tax on the gain</li>
    <li><a href="/crypto-tax-calculator/">Crypto tax calculator</a> — basis for coins and tokens</li>
    <li><a href="/dividend-tax-calculator/">Dividend tax calculator</a> — reinvested dividends add basis</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    A basis and gain estimate. Your broker's 1099-B is the record the IRS matches
    against. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
